	<article id="post-910" class="post-910 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-africa-2 category-citizenship category-the-sociology-of-citizenship">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=910" title="Permalink to Afropolitanism: Global Citizenship with African Routes" rel="bookmark">Afropolitanism: Global Citizenship with African Routes</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=910" title="12:54 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2015-04-04T12:54:04+00:00" pubdate>April 4, 2015</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?author=2" title="View all posts by blogeditor" rel="author">blogeditor</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
						<div class="comments-link">
				<a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=910#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Reply</span></a>			</div>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship.jpg"><img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-795" src="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship-150x150.jpg" alt="Sociology of citizenship" width="150" height="150" /></a><em>By Alpha Abebe</em></p>
<p>Diasporas and other transnational communities have become particularly useful case studies for scholars interested in stretching and challenging mainstream conceptions of citizenship. It is now widely accepted that for many people around the world, physical location and formal legal citizenship may not be the most salient forms of social, political or economic affiliation. As the process of globalization continues to expand, more and more people find themselves in one place, while their lives are structured and oriented by connections to one or several other places. Some of these ‘places’ are other nation states, such as an ancestral country of origin. However, many such ‘places’ exist extraterritorially as abstract yet powerful expressions of identity, community, and belonging. <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=910#more-910" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&rarr;</span></a></p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
		<footer class="entry-meta">
												<span class="cat-links">
				<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-cat-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=59" rel="category">Africa</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=95" rel="category">citizenship</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=98" rel="category">The Sociology of Citizenship</a>			</span>
									
									<span class="sep"> | </span>
						<span class="comments-link"><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=910#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Leave a reply</span></a></span>
			
					</footer><!-- #entry-meta -->
	</article><!-- #post-910 -->

				
					
	<article id="post-902" class="post-902 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-citizenship category-latin-america category-the-sociology-of-citizenship">
		<header class="entry-header">
						<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902" title="Permalink to Questioning traditional citizenship: memory, identity and collective action in Chile" rel="bookmark">Questioning traditional citizenship: memory, identity and collective action in Chile</a></h1>
			
						<div class="entry-meta">
				<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902" title="3:27 pm" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2015-03-13T15:27:06+00:00" pubdate>March 13, 2015</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?author=2" title="View all posts by blogeditor" rel="author">blogeditor</a></span></span>			</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
			
						<div class="comments-link">
				<a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Reply</span></a>			</div>
					</header><!-- .entry-header -->

				<div class="entry-content">
			<p><em><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship.jpg"><img class="alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-795" src="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Sociology-of-citizenship-150x150.jpg" alt="Sociology of citizenship" width="150" height="150" /></a>By Simón Escoffier</em></p>
<p>In this post I contest traditional liberal conceptions of citizenship rooted in the nation-state and consider the role played by memory in the ways in which Santiago de Chile’s disenfranchised produce contentious politics.</p>
<p>I suggest that, by referring to the past in their meetings and conversations, local neighbourhood organisations in Santiago de Chile’s poor settlements (<em>poblaciones</em>) assert a particular, anti-hegemonic interpretation of history. Through stories, historical anecdotes, and different types of memorials, poor residents produce a neighbourhood identity, giving rise to innovative forms of community membership. <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902#more-902" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="meta-nav">&rarr;</span></a></p>
					</div><!-- .entry-content -->
		
		<footer class="entry-meta">
												<span class="cat-links">
				<span class="entry-utility-prep entry-utility-prep-cat-links">Posted in</span> <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=95" rel="category">citizenship</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=77" rel="category">Latin America</a>, <a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?cat=98" rel="category">The Sociology of Citizenship</a>			</span>
									
									<span class="sep"> | </span>
						<span class="comments-link"><a href="http://blog.qeh.ox.ac.uk/?p=902#respond"><span class="leave-reply">Leave a reply</span></a></span>
			
